Ingredients for use in Data Science Recipes

There are lots of data science recipes, but many of them are created from a common set of ingredients. We can spend more or less time on becoming familiar with these ingredients depending on

  • The recipies you are interested in (emphasize most useful)
  • The ingredients you are already feel comfortable with (avoid the most familiar)

Graphics

Packages: ggformula, mosaic

Plots like this are simple to make in R:

Graphics

Packages: ggformula, mosaic

Tidy Data and Data Wrangling

Packages: dplyr, tidyr, etc.

Often we need to transform data into the proper format for analysis or graphics.

Tidy data:

  • rows = observational units/cases/subjects
  • columns = variables
  • no exceptions, no "extras" (units, summaries, comments, meta-data, etc.)

Data scraping

Packages: rvest

  • Lots of data available online
  • May require some work to put a in the proper format (wrangling)

Importing your own data

Packages: readr, googlesheets, readxl, haven

R is capable of reading data in a wide variety of formats

  • general-purpose formats: csv, tsv, fixed width

  • data from other software: Excel, Google spreadsheets, SAS, SPSS

  • databases: MySQL, MS SQLServer, etc.

  • specialized data fromats: shape files for maps, FASTA files for genetics, etc.

If you have data you want to use in R, we can help you get it into R.

Packages: rmarkdown, bookdown, blogdown, knitr, flexdashboard, etc.

RStudio provides a rich set of authoring tools to produce static and dynamic documents in a variety of formats (HTML, PDF, Word)

  • RStudio quick tour

Apps – interactivity, but no visible code

Packages: shiny, shinydocs

"Advanced" R

Don't let "advanced" scare you off. They are things that many people don't get around to learning early on, but they are not terribly difficult.

  • Writing Functions

  • Creating Packages

  • How the R language works (inspecting objects, avoiding inefficient "loops", using C++ inside R, etc.)

  • Hadley Wickham's Advanced R (online) book

Modeling – Don't forget Statistics!

Packages: many

R can fit an incredibly wide range of statistical models.

  • Linear regression (and generalizations)
  • Machine Learning
  • Simulation-based methods (Bootstrap, Randomization, Validation methods)
  • Bayesian methods
  • etc, etc, etc
